    <h1>Editing categories</h1><div id="preamble">
<div class="sectionbody">
<div class="paragraph">
<p><strong>plentymarkets » Item » Categories</strong></p>
</div>
</div>
</div><div class="sect1">
<h2 id="_setting_the_category_levels">1. Setting the category levels</h2>
<div class="sectionbody">
<div class="paragraph">
<p>First decide how many category levels should be displayed in your online store. For example, if you enter 4, then no categories can be created on the 5th level.</p>
</div>
<div class="paragraph instruction">
<p>Setting the category levels:</p>
</div>
<div class="olist arabic">
<ol class="arabic">
<li>
<p>Go to <strong>Settings » Client (store) » Standard » Categories » Basic settings</strong>.</p>
</li>
<li>
<p>Select the maximum number of levels in the category navigation.</p>
</li>
<li>
<p><strong>Save</strong> the setting.</p>
</li>
</ol>
</div>
</div>
</div><div class="sect1">
<h2 id="_creating_a_category">2. Creating a category</h2>
<div class="sectionbody">
<div class="paragraph">
<p>Create a category whenever you want to add a new item category or a page with information to your online store. You must have created a main category before you can create subcategories underneath it. Some categories are already in your system by default. One of these default categories is the category <strong>Content</strong>.</p>
</div>
<div class="admonitionblock important">
<table>
<tbody><tr>
<td class="icon">
<i class="fa icon-important" title="Important"></i>
</td>
<td class="content">
<div class="title">Default category "Content"</div>
<div class="paragraph">
<p>You cannot change the name or the URL name of the category <strong>Content</strong>. You can change settings that do not relate to the name, e.g. the position. You can not create additional categories called <strong>Content</strong>.</p>
</div>
</td>
</tr>
</tbody></table>
</div>
<div class="paragraph">
<p>Learn more about creating categories in the following video tutorial:</p>
</div>
<div class="paragraph linkBox">
<p><a href="https://www.plentymarkets.co.uk/a-3409/" target="_blank">Creating categories</a></p>
</div>
<div class="admonitionblock tip">
<table>
<tbody><tr>
<td class="icon">
<i class="fa icon-tip" title="Tip"></i>
</td>
<td class="content">
<div class="title">Tip: Planning a structure</div>
<div class="paragraph">
<p>Set up a logical category structure before you begin creating categories.<br>
Before you begin creating item categories, consider which products are included in your portfolio and divide these products into groups of categories and subcategories.<br>
For example, you could use Women’s clothing and Men’s clothing as parent categories and then use Shoes as a subcategory of each one. Or you could set up categories the other way around. You could use Shoes as a parent category and have it include the subcategories Women’s and Men’s. Set up the categories that best match your portfolio.</p>
</div>
</td>
</tr>
</tbody></table>
</div>
<div class="sect2">
<h3 id="_creating_a_main_category">2.1. Creating a main category</h3>
<div class="paragraph">
<p>The following section explains how to create new main categories.</p>
</div>
<div class="paragraph instruction">
<p>Creating a main category:</p>
</div>
<div class="olist arabic">
<ol class="arabic">
<li>
<p>Go to <strong>Item » Categories</strong>.</p>
</li>
<li>
<p>Click on the <strong>New category</strong> button in the lower left corner.<br>
→ The <strong>Create new category</strong> window will open.</p>
</li>
<li>
<p>Enter a <strong>name</strong> for the category.</p>
</li>
<li>
<p>Select <strong>Main category</strong> as the category level.</p>
</li>
<li>
<p>Click on <strong>Create</strong> to create the category.<br>
→ The category will be created and displayed in the directory tree on the left.</p>
</li>
</ol>
</div>
<div class="admonitionblock tip">
<table>
<tbody><tr>
<td class="icon">
<i class="fa icon-tip" title="Tip"></i>
</td>
<td class="content">
<div class="title">Category type</div>
<div class="paragraph">
<p>New categories are assigned the category type <strong>Item</strong> by default (table 2).</p>
</div>
</td>
</tr>
</tbody></table>
</div>
</div>
<div class="sect2">
<h3 id="_creating_a_subcategory">2.2. Creating a subcategory</h3>
<div class="paragraph">
<p>There are two different ways to create subcategories.</p>
</div>
<div class="paragraph instruction">
<p>Creating a subcategory using the button:</p>
</div>
<div class="olist arabic">
<ol class="arabic">
<li>
<p>Go to <strong>Item » Categories</strong>.</p>
</li>
<li>
<p>Click on the <strong>New category</strong> button in the lower left corner.<br>
→ The <strong>Create new category</strong> window will open.</p>
</li>
<li>
<p>Enter a <strong>name</strong> for the category.</p>
</li>
<li>
<p>Select <strong>Subcategory</strong> as the category level.</p>
</li>
<li>
<p>Select which main category this new subcategory should be included in.</p>
</li>
<li>
<p>Click on <strong>Create</strong> to create the category.<br>
→ The category will be created and displayed as a subcategory in the directory tree on the left.</p>
</li>
<li>
<p>Click on a main category to display its subcategories.</p>
</li>
</ol>
</div>
<div class="paragraph instruction">
<p>Creating a new subcategory with the context menu:</p>
</div>
<div class="olist arabic">
<ol class="arabic">
<li>
<p>Go to <strong>Item » Categories</strong>.</p>
</li>
<li>
<p>Open the category to which you want to add a subcategory.</p>
</li>
<li>
<p>Use your mouse to right-click on a category.<br>
→ The context menu will open.</p>
</li>
<li>
<p>Click on <strong>Create subcategory</strong>.<br>
→ The <strong>Create new subcategory</strong> window will open.</p>
</li>
<li>
<p>Enter a <strong>name</strong> for the subcategory.</p>
</li>
<li>
<p>Click on <strong>Create</strong> to create the category.<br>
→ The category will be created and displayed as a subcategory in the directory tree on the left.</p>
</li>
<li>
<p>Click on a main category to display its subcategories.</p>
</li>
</ol>
</div>
<div class="paragraph">
<p>If you want to create a subcategory on the 3rd or 4th level, click on the categories until you have reached the category that should include the new subcategory.</p>
</div>
<div class="admonitionblock important">
<table>
<tbody><tr>
<td class="icon">
<i class="fa icon-important" title="Important"></i>
</td>
<td class="content">
<div class="title">Activate categories</div>
<div class="paragraph">
<p>You have to activate a category in order for it to be visible in the online store. Go to <strong>Settings » Client (store) » Standard » Categories » Activate</strong> to activate the categories.</p>
</div>
</td>
</tr>
</tbody></table>
</div>
</div>
</div>
</div><div class="sect1">
<h2 id="_editing_a_category">3. Editing a category</h2>
<div class="sectionbody">
<div class="paragraph">
<p>Categories that were already created are found in the directory tree on the left. They can now be edited. Click on a category to open it. Or right-click on a category to open its context menu. The context menu gives you quick access to certain functions, e.g. to edit, move, copy or delete a category. You can also create a new item or a subcategory.</p>
</div>
<div class="admonitionblock important">
<table>
<tbody><tr>
<td class="icon">
<i class="fa icon-important" title="Important"></i>
</td>
<td class="content">
<div class="title">Copying a category</div>
<div class="paragraph">
<p>The <strong>Copy category</strong> function allows you to create the same subcategory in several different parent categories. For example, this is useful if you want to have categories for women’s, men’s and children’s clothing, and all three categories should include pants as a subcategory. Copy the category with all of its settings and then make changes to the name and the description as needed.</p>
</div>
</td>
</tr>
</tbody></table>
</div>
<div class="paragraph">
<p>The editing window is divided into 5 tabs. These tabs are: <strong>Settings</strong>, <strong>Description 1</strong>, <strong>Description 2</strong>, <strong>Documents</strong> and <strong>Note</strong>. A toolbar is located above the tabs. This toolbar is described in table 1.</p>
</div>
